d himself on the Potomac River in what was then Stafford County, VA, as a planter and exporter. He also practiced law, was a member of the Virginia House of Burgesses, and served in 1687 as lieutenant colonel of the county militia."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Mabella","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern name, apparently derived from   Isabella   by the dropping of the initial vowel."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Mabella FitzHugh was born about 1100, in Malpas, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert d'Avranches, was 31 and her mother, Adeliza de Dol, was 28. She had at least 1 son with William Le Belward de Malpas I.. She died in 1175, in Malpas, Cheshire, England, at the age of 76."},"et":{"about 1100–1175":"umbes 1100–1175","1100–1175":"1100–1175","1090–1134":"1090–1134","1140–1181":"1140–1181","1070–1130":"1070–1130","1073–Female":"1073–Surnud","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1090":"1090","1175":"1175","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1073":"1073","1181":"1181","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1134":"1134","1100"